# Cursor Rules - Global Configuration

## Code Style and Formatting
- Use Python 3.11+ syntax and features
- Follow PEP 8 style guidelines
- Use type hints for all function parameters and return values
- Use descriptive variable and function names
- Write comprehensive docstrings for all functions and classes

## Documentation and Comments
- Write all documentation and comments in English
- Use clear, concise language
- Avoid informal language and humor
- Provide technical, direct, and neutral responses
- Keep answers brief and to the point

## Emoji Policy - STRICTLY ENFORCED
- NEVER use emojis in any code, documentation, comments, or responses
- Remove any existing emojis from code and documentation
- Use plain text alternatives for status indicators
- Examples:
  - Use "Success" instead of "✅ Success"
  - Use "Error" instead of "❌ Error"
  - Use "Info" instead of "ℹ️ Info"
  - Use "Warning" instead of "⚠️ Warning"

## Architecture Guidelines
- Follow Clean Architecture principles
- Implement SOLID design patterns
- Use dependency injection where appropriate
- Separate concerns between layers (domain, infrastructure, presentation)
- Write testable code with proper mocking

## Testing Requirements
- Maintain 100% test coverage for all new code
- Write unit tests for all business logic
- Write integration tests for external dependencies
- Use pytest for all testing
- Mock external services and APIs

## Error Handling
- Use appropriate exception types
- Provide meaningful error messages
- Log errors with appropriate levels
- Handle edge cases gracefully

## Security
- Never hardcode API keys or sensitive data
- Use environment variables for configuration
- Validate all user inputs
- Follow secure coding practices

## Performance
- Optimize database queries
- Use async/await for I/O operations
- Implement proper caching where appropriate
- Monitor and log performance metrics

## File Organization
- Keep related functionality together
- Use clear directory structure
- Follow Python package conventions
- Maintain consistent naming patterns

## Git and Version Control
- Write clear, descriptive commit messages
- Use conventional commit format
- Keep commits atomic and focused
- Document breaking changes

## Code Quality
- Use linting tools (flake8, black, mypy)
- Fix all linting errors before committing
- Use meaningful variable names
- Avoid code duplication
- Write self-documenting code

## API Design
- Use RESTful principles
- Provide clear API documentation
- Use appropriate HTTP status codes
- Implement proper error responses
- Version APIs appropriately

## Database
- Use proper database migrations
- Implement proper indexing
- Use connection pooling
- Handle database errors gracefully
- Use transactions where appropriate

## Logging
- Use structured logging
- Include relevant context in log messages
- Use appropriate log levels
- Avoid logging sensitive information
- Implement log rotation

## Configuration
- Use environment variables for configuration
- Provide sensible defaults
- Validate configuration on startup
- Document all configuration options
- Use configuration files where appropriate

## Dependencies
- Keep dependencies up to date
- Use specific version pinning
- Document all dependencies
- Avoid unnecessary dependencies
- Use virtual environments

## Documentation
- Keep README.md up to date
- Document all public APIs
- Provide usage examples
- Document configuration options
- Keep architecture documentation current

## Monitoring and Observability
- Implement health checks
- Use proper metrics collection
- Implement distributed tracing
- Monitor application performance
- Set up alerting for critical issues

## Deployment
- Use containerization (Docker)
- Implement proper CI/CD pipelines
- Use infrastructure as code
- Implement proper secrets management
- Use environment-specific configurations

## Compliance
- Follow data protection regulations
- Implement proper access controls
- Use secure communication protocols
- Implement audit logging
- Follow industry best practices

## Communication
- Use clear, professional language
- Provide technical, direct responses
- Avoid humor and informal language
- Keep responses brief and to the point
- Use Portuguese-BR for user communication, English for code and documentation
